# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: air-start-system
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:air-start-system/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:air-start-system/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] An **air compressor** is a machine that takes ambient air from the surroundings and discharges it at a higher pressure.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] It is an application of a gas compressor and a pneumatic device that converts mechanical power (from an electric motor, diesel or gasoline engine, etc.) into potential energy stored in compressed air, which has many uses.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] A common application is to compress air into a storage tank, for immediate or later use.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] When the delivery pressure reaches its set upper limit, the compressor is shut off, or the excess air is released through an overpressure valve.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] The compressed air is stored in the tank until it is needed.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] The pressure energy provided by the compressed air can be used for a variety of applications such as pneumatic tools as it is released.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] When tank pressure reaches its lower limit, the air compressor turns on again and re-pressurizes the tank.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] A compressor is different from a pump because it works on a gas, while pumps work on a liquid.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] There are numerous methods of air compression, divided into either positive-displacement or roto-dynamic types.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Positive-displacement compressors work by forcing air through a chamber whose volume is decreased to compress the air.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Once the pressure is greater than the pressure outside the discharge valve, a port or valve opens and air is discharged into the outlet system from the compression chamber.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] The capacities for both single-stage and two-stage compressors are generally specified in Standard Cubic feet per Minute (SCFM) or litres per minute and pounds per square Inch (PSI) or bar.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] To a lesser extent, some compressors are rated in actual cubic feet per minute (ACFM).
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Still others are rated in cubic feet per minute (CFM).
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Using CFM alone to rate a compressor is ambiguous because it represents a flow rate without a pressure reference. i.e.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Single stage compressors usually fall into the fractional through 5 horsepower range.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Two-stage compressors normally fall into the 5 through 30 horsepower range.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Roto-dynamic air compressors include centrifugal compressors where Rotating vanes impart kinetic energy to a gas and stationary passages convert velocity into a rise in pressure, and axial compressors, where rotor blades impart the kinetic energy and stator blades convert it to a rise in pressure.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Due to adiabatic heating, air compressors require some method of disposing of waste heat.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Generally this is some form of air- or water-cooling, although some (particularly rotary type) compressors may be cooled by oil (that is then in turn air- or water-cooled).
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] The atmospheric changes are also considered during cooling of compressors.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] The type of cooling is determined by considering the factors such as inlet temperature, ambient temperature, power of the compressor and area of application.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] There is no single type of compressor that could be used for any application.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Air compressors are also widely used in oil and gas, mining and drilling applications as the flushing medium, aerating muds in underbalanced drilling and in air pigging of pipelines.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Most air compressors either are reciprocating piston type, rotary vane or rotary screw.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Centrifugal compressors are common in very large applications, while rotary screw, scroll, and reciprocating air compressors are favoured for small and medium-sized applications.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Air compressors are designed to utilize a variety of power sources.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] While direct drive gasoline or diesel-engines and electric motors are among the most popular, air compressors that utilize vehicle engines, power-take-off, or hydraulic ports are also commonly used in mobile applications.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] The power of a compressor is measured in HP (horsepower) and CFM (cubic feet per minute of intake air).
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] The volume of the pressure vessel and the stored pressure indicate the volume of compressed air (in reserve) available.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Gasoline and diesel-powered compressors are widely used in remote areas with problematic access to electricity.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] They are noisy and require ventilation for exhaust gases, particularly if the compressed air is to be used for a breathing air supply.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Electric-powered compressors are widely used in production, workshops and garages with permanent access to electricity.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Common workshop/garage compressors are 110-120 Volt or 230-240 Volt.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Compressor tank shapes are: "pancake", "twin tank", "horizontal", and "vertical".
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Depending on a size and purpose compressors can be stationary or portable.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] To ensure all compressor types run efficiently with no leaks, it is necessary to perform routine maintenance.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] The cost of maintenance only accounts for 8% of the life cycle cost of owning an air compressor.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] According to CAGI air compressor performance verification data sheets, the higher the isentropic efficiency is, the better the energy saving is.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] The better air compressor isentropic efficiency has reached 95%.
[src:air-start-system/air-compressor] Approximately 70~80% of the air compressor's total lifetime cost is energy consumption, so using the high-efficiency air compressor is one of the energy-saving methods.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] An **air-start system** is a power source used to provide the initial rotation to start large diesel engines and gas turbines.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Compared to a gasoline (petrol) engine, a diesel engine has a very high compression ratio, an essential design feature, as it is the heat of compression that ignites the fuel.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] An electric starter with sufficient power to turn a large diesel engine would itself be so large as to be impractical so there is a need for an alternative system.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] An air start system has three main components along with various safety components, namely the air start injector, the distributor and the air receivers.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] When the system is initiated, starting air from the receivers is distributed by the distributor unit to each respective air start valve according to the firing order of the engine’s cylinders.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Safety components include flame traps, to prevent air line explosions, a turning gear interlock which ensures that air-start cannot be initiated when the turning gear is engaged, relief valves and isolation valves, as well as drain valves at certain points along the system.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Control components include the control valves and remote air-start valves.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] A direct start system as used on a marine slow-speed diesel is required to have up to 12 starts on a non-reversing engine or 6 starts on a reversible, or geared, engine.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] When starting the engine, compressed air is admitted to whichever cylinder has a piston just over top dead center, forcing it downward.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] As the engine starts to turn, the air-start valve on the next cylinder in line opens to continue the rotation.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] After several rotations, fuel is injected into the cylinders, the engine starts running and the air is cut off.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] To further complicate matters, a large engine is usually "blown over" first with zero fuel settings and the indicator cocks open, to prove that the engine is clear of any water build up and that everything is free to turn.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] After a successful blow ahead and a blow astern, the indicator cocks are closed on all the cylinders, and then the engine can be started on fuel.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Significant complexity is added to the engine by using an air-start system, as the cylinder head must have an extra valve in each cylinder to admit the air in for starting, plus the required control systems.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] This added complexity and cost limits the use of air-starters to very large and expensive reciprocating engines.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Another method of air-starting an internal combustion engine is by using compressed air or gas to drive a fluid motor in place of an electric motor.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] They can be used to start engines from 5 to 320 liters in size and if more starting power is necessary two or more motors can be used.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Starters of this type are used in place of electric motors because of their lighter weight and higher reliability.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] They can also outlast an electric starter by a factor of three and are easier to rebuild.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Engines operating in underground mining activities tend to operate on this type of starter system to reduce the risk of an electrical system igniting flammable material.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] All vane type air starters should have a lubricator installed to insure long-life and maximum performance.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Lubricators give the moving parts a needed friction barrier, reduce metal corrosion and keep vanes sealed properly against the cylinder walls.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Even the so-called lube-free air starters require lubrication to prolong trouble free life.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Two basic lubricator devices are typically employed.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] One is an in-line or reservoir type that typically stores up to 2 quarts of lubricant, and is installed along the air supply line.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] The second style of lubricator is a small one shot device that dispenses a measured amount of lubricant every time the starter is engaged.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Installed directly onto the air inlet of the starter, the in-line lubricators are self priming pneumatic pumps that require a 1/4″ lubrication line piped from as far away as 4 feet.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Air Starter lubricators perform best using misting type, non-detergent oils such as diesel fuel or Marvel Mystery oil.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] If emissions are a concern, there are environmentally friendly type lubricants available on the market.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Not all air starters require lubrication.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Turbine type air starters do not require air motor lubrication, although some turbine air starters do use an oil filled transmission that may require periodic inspections and maintenance.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Compressed air has been used to start gas turbine engines using air impingement starting (in which air is directed at the engine turbine blades through nozzles in the turbine casing, used on US Navy General Electric J79 engines).
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] It is much more efficient to use an air turbine starter (ATS) which is usually mounted on an accessory gearbox.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] An early axial compressor turbojet had an ATS located in the compressor nose cone (eg particular variants of the J79).
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Air impingement starting was not used for US military aircraft after the F-4B, A-5A and F-5 as the pneumatic energy requirement was several times greater than when using an air turbine starter.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] The gas turbine compressor required to start a J79 with impingement starting was sufficient to start two J79 engines simultaneously in a B-58 when using air turbine starters.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] An ATS has its own turbine and gears to change its low torque and high speed to low speed and high torque at the engine mounting pad.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Further gears in the engine gearbox connect to the engine shaft (high pressure spool on multi-spool engines).
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] Compared with electric starters, air-starters have a higher power-to-weight ratio so are used on large engines as an electric starter would be too big and, with its cables, too heavy and expensive.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] However, for smaller engines, which don't need as much starter power, an electric starter is more suitable.
[src:air-start-system/air-start-system] It has a dual function as a generator (is known as a starter/generator) at speeds above which the engine no longer requires starter assistance.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] There are many different types of air turborockets.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and many others.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The benefit of this setup is increased specific impulse over that of a rocket.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] For the same carried mass of propellant as a rocket motor, the overall output of the air turborocket is much higher.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] In addition, it provides thrust throughout a much wider speed range than a ramjet, yet is much cheaper and easier to control than a gas turbine engine.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The air turborocket fills a niche (in terms of cost, reliability, ruggedness, and duration of thrust) between the solid-fuel rocket motor and gas turbine engine for missile applications.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] A **turborocket** is a type of aircraft engine combining elements of a jet engine and a rocket.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] It typically comprises a multi-stage fan driven by a turbine, which is driven by the hot gases exhausting from a series of small rocket-like motors mounted around the turbine inlet.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust gases mix with the fan discharge air, and combust with the air from the compressor before exhausting through a convergent-divergent propelling nozzle.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] Once a jet engine goes high enough in an atmosphere, there is insufficient oxygen to burn the jet fuel.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The idea behind a turborocket is to supplement the atmospheric oxygen with an onboard supply.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] This allows operation at a much higher altitude than a normal engine would allow.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The turborocket design offers a mixture of benefits with drawbacks.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] It is not a true rocket, so it cannot operate in space.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] Cooling the engine is not a problem because the burner and its hot exhaust gases are located behind the turbine blades.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The air turboramjet engine is a combined cycle engine that merges aspects of turbojet and ramjet engines.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The turboramjet is a hybrid engine that essentially consists of a turbojet mounted inside a ramjet.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The turbojet core is mounted inside a duct that contains a combustion chamber downstream of the turbojet nozzle.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The turboramjet can be run in turbojet mode at takeoff and during low-speed flight but then switch to ramjet mode to accelerate to high Mach numbers.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The operation of the engine is controlled using bypass flaps located just downstream of the diffuser.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] During low-speed flight, controllable flaps close the bypass duct and force air directly into the compressor section of the turbojet.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] During high-speed flight, the flaps block the flow into the turbojet, and the engine operates like a ramjet using the *aft* combustion chamber to produce thrust.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The engine would start out operating as a turbojet during takeoff and while climbing to altitude.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] Upon reaching high subsonic speed, the portion of the engine downstream of the turbojet would be used as an afterburner to accelerate the plane above the speed of sound.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] At lower speeds, air passes through an inlet and is then compressed by an axial compressor.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] That compressor is driven by a turbine, which is powered by hot, high-pressure gas from a combustion chamber.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] These initial aspects are very similar to how a turbojet operates, however, there are several differences.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The first is that the combustor in the turboramjet is often separate from the main airflow.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] Instead of combining air from the compressor with fuel to combust, the turboramjet combustor may use hydrogen and oxygen, carried on the aircraft, as its fuel for the combustor.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The air compressed by the compressor bypasses the combustor and turbine section of the engine, where it is mixed with the turbine exhaust.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust can be designed to be fuel-rich (i.e., the combustor does not burn all the fuel) which, when mixed with the compressed air, creates a hot fuel-air mixture which is ready to burn again.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] More fuel is injected into this air where it is again combusted.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The exhaust is ejected through a propelling nozzle, generating thrust.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] Picture shown lacks required bypass ducting around the compressor for ramjet operation.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] Shown is a low bypass turbojet with re-heat.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] The turboramjet engine is used when space is constrained, as it takes up less space than separate ramjet and turbojet engines.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] Since a ramjet must already be traveling at high speeds before it will start working, a ramjet-powered aircraft is incapable of taking off from a runway under its own power; that is the advantage of the turbojet, which is a member of the gas turbine family of engines.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] A turbojet does not rely purely on the motion of the engine to compress the incoming air flow; instead, the turbojet contains some additional rotating machinery that compresses incoming air and allows the engine to function during takeoff and at slow speeds.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] In applications which stay relatively in the atmosphere and require longer durations of lower thrust over a specific speed range the air turborocket can have a weight advantage over the standard solid fuel rocket motor.
[src:air-start-system/air-turborocket] In terms of volumetric requirements, the rocket motor has the advantage due to the lack of inlet ducts and other air management devices.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-controls] *Right* - The left magneto p-lead is grounded, and the right is open.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-controls] This disables the left magneto and enables the right magneto only.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-controls] *Left* - The right magneto p-lead is grounded, and the left is open.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-controls] This disables the right magneto and enables the left magneto only.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-controls] *Both* - This is the normal operating configuration, both p-leads are open, enabling both magnetos.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-controls] *Start* - The pinion gear on the starter motor is engaged with the flywheel and the starter motor runs to turn the engine over.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-controls] In most cases, only the left magneto is active (the right p-lead is grounded) due to timing differences between the magnetos at low RPMs.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-controls] In an aircraft with a **fixed-pitch propeller**, there is no direct control over the propeller rotational speed, which depends on the airspeed and loading.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-controls] Therefore, the pilot has to pay attention to the RPM indicator and adjust the throttle/power lever in order to maintain the desired constant speed of the propeller.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-controls] For example, when the airspeed reduces and the loading increases (e.g., in a climb), RPM will decrease and the pilot has to increase the throttle/power.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-controls] When the airspeed increases and the loading decreases (e.g., in a dive), the RPM will increase and the pilot has to decrease the throttle/power in order to prevent RPM from exceeding the operational limits and damaging the motor.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-controls] Restricting the volume of cooling airflow too much.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-controls] Insufficient delivery of lubricating oil to the engine's moving parts.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Many variations of **aircraft engine starting** have been used since the Wright brothers made their first powered flight in 1903.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] The methods used have been designed for weight saving, simplicity of operation and reliability.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Early piston engines were started by hand.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Geared hand starting, electrical and cartridge-operated systems for larger engines were developed between the First and Second World Wars.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Gas turbine aircraft engines such as turbojets, turboshafts and turbofans often use air/pneumatic starting, with the use of *bleed air* from built-in auxiliary power units (APUs) or external air compressors now seen as a common starting method.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Often only one engine needs be started using the APU (or remote compressor).
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] After the first engine is started using APU bleed air, *cross-bleed air* from the running engine can be used to start the remaining engine(s).
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Hand starting of aircraft piston engines by swinging the propeller is the oldest and simplest method, the absence of any onboard starting system giving an appreciable weight saving.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Positioning of the propeller relative to the crankshaft is arranged such that the engine pistons pass through top dead centre during the swinging stroke.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] As the ignition system is normally arranged to produce sparks before top dead centre there is a risk of the engine kicking back during hand starting.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] To avoid this problem one of the two magnetos used in a typical aero engine ignition system is fitted with an 'impulse coupling', a spring-loaded device which delays the spark until top dead centre and which also increases the rotational speed of the magneto to produce a stronger spark.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] When the engine fires, the impulse coupling no longer operates and the second magneto is switched on.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Note that this is different from the manual "turning over" of a radial piston engine, which is done to release oil that has become trapped in the lower cylinders prior to starting to avoid engine damage.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] The two appear similar, but while hand starting involves a sharp, strong "yank" on the prop to start the engine, turning over is simply done by turning the prop through a certain set amount.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Accidents have occurred during lone pilot hand starting, whether due to high throttle settings, brakes not having been applied, or wheel chocks not being used, all resulting in the aircraft moving off without the pilot at the controls.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] The Hucks starter (invented by Bentfield Hucks during WWI) is a mechanical replacement for the ground crew.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Based on a vehicle chassis the device uses a clutch driven shaft to turn the propeller, disengaging as the engine starts.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] A Hucks starter is used regularly at the Shuttleworth Collection for starting period aircraft.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Self-sustaining motor gliders (often known as 'turbos') are fitted with small two-stroke engines with no starting system, for ground testing a cord is wrapped around the propeller boss and pulled rapidly in conjunction with operating decompressor valves.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] These engines are started in flight by operating the decompressor and increasing airspeed to windmill the propeller.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Early variants of the Slingsby Falke motor glider use a cockpit mounted pull start system.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Aircraft began to be equipped with electrical systems around 1930, powered by a battery and small wind-driven generator.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] The systems were initially not powerful enough to drive starter motors.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Introduction of engine-driven generators solved the problem.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Introduction of electric starter motors for aero engines increased convenience at the expense of extra weight and complexity.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] They were a necessity for flying boats with high mounted, inaccessible engines.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Powered by an onboard battery, ground electrical supply or both, the starter is operated by a key or switch in the cockpit.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] The key system usually facilitates switching of the magnetos.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] In cold ambient conditions the friction caused by viscous engine oil causes a high load on the starting system.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Another problem is the reluctance of the fuel to vaporise and combust at low temperatures.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Oil dilution systems were developed (mixing fuel with the engine oil), and engine pre-heaters were used (including lighting fires under the engine).
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] The Ki-Gass priming pump system was used to assist starting of British engines.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Aircraft fitted with variable-pitch propellers or constant speed propellers are started in fine pitch to reduce air loads and current in the starter motor circuit.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Many light aircraft are fitted with a 'starter engaged' warning light in the cockpit, a mandatory airworthiness requirement to guard against the risk of the starter motor failing to disengage from the engine.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] The Coffman starter was an explosive cartridge operated device, the burning gases either operating directly in the cylinders to rotate the engine or operating through a geared drive.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] First introduced on the Junkers Jumo 205 diesel engine in 1936 the Coffman starter was not widely used by civil operators due to the expense of the cartridges.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] In 1920 Roy Fedden designed a piston engine gas starting system, used on the Bristol Jupiter engine in 1922.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] A system used in early Rolls-Royce Kestrel engines ducted high-pressure air from a ground unit through a camshaft driven distributor to the cylinders via non-return valves, the system had disadvantages only overcome by conversion to electric starting.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] When a piston engine needs to be started in flight the electric starter motor can be used.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] This is a normal procedure for motor gliders that have been soaring with the engine turned off.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] During aerobatics with earlier aircraft types it was not uncommon for the engine to cut during manoeuvres due to carburettor design.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] With no electric starter installed, engines can be restarted by diving the aircraft to increase airspeed and the rotation speed of the 'windmilling' propeller.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] An aero engine inertia starter uses a pre-rotated flywheel to transfer kinetic energy to the crankshaft, normally through reduction gears and a clutch to prevent over-torque conditions.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Three variations have been used, hand driven, electrically driven and a combination of both.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] When the flywheel is fully energised either a manual cable is pulled or a solenoid is used to engage the starter.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Starting of a gas turbine engine requires rotation of the compressor to a speed that provides sufficient pressurised air to the combustion chambers.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] The starting system has to overcome inertia of the compressor and friction loads, the system remains in operation after combustion starts and is disengaged once the engine has reached self-idling speed.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Two types of electrical starter motor can be used, direct-cranking (to disengage as internal combustion engines) and starter-generator system (permanently engaged).
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Small gas turbine engines, particularly turboshaft engines used in helicopters and cruise missile turbojets can be started by a geared hydraulic motor using oil pressure from a ground supply.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] With air-start systems, gas turbine engine compressor spools are rotated by the action of a large volume of compressed air acting directly on the compressor blades or driving the engine through a small, geared turbine motor.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] These motors can weigh up to 75% less than an equivalent electrical system.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] The compressed air can be supplied from an on-board auxiliary power unit (APU), a portable gas generator used by ground crew or by cross feeding bleed air from a running engine in the case of multi-engined aircraft.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] The Turbomeca Palouste gas generator was used to start the Spey engines of the Blackburn Buccaneer.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] The de Havilland Sea Vixen was equipped with its own Palouste in a removable underwing container to facilitate starting when away from base.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Other military aircraft types using ground supplied compressed air for starting include the Lockheed F-104 Starfighter and variants of the F-4 Phantom using the General Electric J79 turbojet engine.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Versions of the Rolls-Royce Avon turbojet engine used a geared turbine starter motor that burned isopropyl nitrate as the fuel.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] In military service this monofuel had the NATO designation of S-746 AVPIN.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] For starting a measured amount of fuel was introduced to the starter combustion chamber then ignited electrically, the hot gases spinning the turbine at high revolutions with the exhaust exiting overboard.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Similar in operating principle to the piston engine Coffman starter, an explosive cartridge drives a small turbine engine which is connected by gears to the compressor shaft.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Developed for short-haul airliners, most civil and military aircraft requiring self-contained starting systems these units are known by various names including Auxiliary Power Unit (APU), Jet Fuel Starter (JFS), Air Start Unit (ASU) or Gas Turbine Compressor (GTC).
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Comprising a small gas turbine which is electrically started, these devices provide compressed bleed air for engine starting and often also provide electrical and hydraulic power for ground operations without the need to run the main engines.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Two small petrol/oil mix tanks were fitted in the annular intake.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] The Lockheed SR-71 Blackbird used two Buick Nailheads as starter motors, which were mounted on an AG-330 Start Kart trolley, later with Chevrolet big-block 454-cubic-inch (7.44 L) V8 engines.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Gas turbine engines can be shut down in flight, intentionally by the crew to save fuel or during a flight test or unintentionally due to fuel starvation or flameout after a compressor stall.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Sufficient airspeed is used to 'windmill' the compressor then fuel and ignition are switched on, an on-board auxiliary power unit may be used at high altitudes where the air density is lower.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] During zoom climb operations of the Lockheed NF-104A the jet engine was shut down on climbing through 85,000 ft (26,000 m) and was started using the windmill method on descent through denser air.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Pulse jet engines are uncommon aircraft powerplants.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] However, the Argus As 014 used to power the V-1 flying bomb and Fieseler Fi 103R Reichenberg was a notable exception.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Once the engine started and the temperature rose to the minimum operating level, the external air hose and connectors were removed, and the resonant design of the tailpipe kept the pulse jet firing.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] Each cycle or pulse of the engine began with the shutters open; fuel was injected behind them and ignited, and the resulting expansion of gases forced the shutters closed.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] As the pressure in the engine dropped following combustion, the shutters reopened and the cycle was repeated, roughly 40 to 45 times per second.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine-starting] The electrical ignition system was used only to start the engine; heating of the tailpipe skin maintained combustion.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:air-start-system/aircraft-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
